I am improving at drawing at a steady rate, but the more I know and the better I get the more I realize how much there still is to learn. And the awareness of the things you lack grows a lot faster and gets a lot bigger than your actual knowledge and abilities.
It's incredibly easy to get lost in that and see everything you have worked so hard for as a pebble next to a mountain, small, meaningless and insignificant.

I've gotten good at not letting that overwhelm me most of the time, but sometimes it still happens.

In those cases it's good to remind yourself that fixating yourself on that will never help you go forward, in fact it's self-sabotage. The simple truth of learning anything is that you suck ass at something until you don't.
So I give my best to only think about any problems I may have with the intent of fixing them. Because there is no sense in wasting your finite lifetime rubbing your problems in you own face instead of doing something about it. Any failed effort will be worth more than having thrown your energy away for nothing.

I don't have to do this every time, because most of the time drawing is fulfilling and enjoyable. But when it isn't I keep the shit I mentioned before in mind and it carries me through.
